ce:section.ce:para:
The schematic of experimental setup is shown in Fig. 1
                        . The system consists of a LIB, metal box (the outer wall is wrapped with insulation cotton, and the inner wall is lined with a rubber insulating mat at the bottom, and the box structure parameters are shown in Table 5
                        ), temperature chamber (ASR-80L), computer, battery test device (LAND CT6001B), temperature test device (Keysight 34970A), gear oil pump (FP-24), thermostatic bath (THY-2030), and flowmeter (QZHI-SETSAIL, DN6). The battery test device is employed to monitor the voltage, current, and capacity of the battery during charging and discharging. Battery data is collected at a sampling rate of 5 s for logging into a computer. The temperature test device is used to monitor the battery temperature in real time, with temperature data being recorded to the computer at a frequency of 5 s. A temperature chamber is employed to simulate different ambient temperatures to study charging and discharging and the preheating performance at different temperatures. The thermostatic bath is connected to the oil pump and metal box to establish a continuous flow cycle. In the experimental process, the silicone oil heated by the thermostatic bath flows into the case through the pump and then flows back to the thermostatic bath after heating the batteries. Until the cell is heated to the target temperature, then the cycle stops. The temperature of the battery is monitored through a T-type thermocouple, which is positioned according to Fig. 1 (c). As shown in Fig. 1 (b), the battery packs were arranged symmetrically so that only the temperatures of batteries 1 through 3 needed to be measured. Therefore, a total of 15 thermocouples were used in this experiment.
